<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
This species is dedicated to Louis-Guillaume Lemonnier (1717-1799), &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<normalizedToken originalValue="associé">associe</normalizedToken>
de 
<normalizedToken originalValue="l’Institut">l'Institut</normalizedToken>
, ci-devant membre de 
<normalizedToken originalValue="l’Académie">l'Academie</normalizedToken>
des sciences, conseiller 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’État">d'Etat</normalizedToken>
honoraire, et premier 
<normalizedToken originalValue="médecin">medecin</normalizedToken>
du Roi
</emphasis>
&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Cuvier, G" journalOrPublisher=")" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="37 - 54" publicationUrl="https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/%C3%89loge_historique_de_Lemmonier" refId="B3" refString="Cuvier, G, 1861. Recueil des eloges historiques. Paris: Firmin Didot Freres (nouv. ed.) 1: 37 - 54, https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/%C3%89loge_historique_de_Lemmonier" title="Recueil des eloges historiques. Paris: Firmin Didot Freres (nouv. ed." url="https://fr.wikisource.org/wiki/%C3%89loge_historique_de_Lemmonier" volume="1" year="1861">Cuvier 1861</bibRefCitation>
) [Associate of the French Institute, former member of the Academy of Sciences, Honorary State Councilor, and First Physician of the King] who herborised with C. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnæus">Linnaeus</normalizedToken>
, J.-J. Rousseau, Antoine and Bernard de Jussieu. We adopt the spelling 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Monier”">&quot;Monier&quot;</normalizedToken>
used by J.-B. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Fusée">Fusee</normalizedToken>
Aublet in his herbarium kept at the Paris Museum and known as &quot;Jean-Jacques Rousseau herbarium&quot; (P-JJR), from the name of its most famous owner.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. Pignal &amp; L. P. Queiroz" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Indigofera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Indigofera monieriana" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monieriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Indigofera monieriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was provisionally assessed as vulnerable based on 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B21" refString="IUCN, 2017. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">IUCN (2017)</bibRefCitation>
criterium B as it presents a restricted EOO (7070 km2) and AOO (32 km2), and its estimated range covers about half of New 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Caledonia’s">Caledonia's</normalizedToken>
main island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00378941.1936.10836355" author="Guillaumin, A" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="294 - 315" refId="B9" refString="Guillaumin, A, 1936. Materiaux pour la flore de la Nouvelle-Caledonie. XL.Revision des Legumineuses. Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France 83 (4-5): 294 - 315, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00378941.1936.10836355" title="Materiaux pour la flore de la Nouvelle-Caledonie. XL. Revision des Legumineuses." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00378941.1936.10836355" volume="83" year="1936">Guillaumin (1936)</bibRefCitation>
noted that several virgate specimens from New Caledonia could not be reported to the typical 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Indigofera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Indigofera australis" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Indigofera australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and he preferred to determine them as 
<taxonomicName genus="I." infraspecific-rank="var." lsidName="I. australis var. gracilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="variety" species="australis" variety="gracilis">I. australis var. gracilis</taxonomicName>
DC. However, a careful examination of the type collection of this variety (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Sieber Fl. Novae. Holl. 380</emphasis>
, G, K, P) shows that the New Caledonian material is clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. australis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the less numerous leaflets (5-9 vs. 17-25 in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. australis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), mostly obovate with an emarginate apex, lower surface whitish or greyish green and inconspicuous venation (vs. leaflets mostly elliptical with acute to rounded apex, green lower surface and raised venation; see Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Comparison between the new species of Indigofera from New Caledonia with the Australian I. australis and the widespread species I. zollingeriana." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BCC99796AD403A8E35F604C08E809DA3" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableUuid="BCC99796AD403A8E35F604C08E809DA3">1</tableCitation>
for further distinctive characters). Besides, 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. australis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to Australia and, although presenting a broad morphological variation (
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson, PG" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Gardens" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="67 - 73" publicationUrl="https://www.jstor.org/stable/23874288" refId="B23" refString="Wilson, PG, Rowe, R, 2010. New taxa and typifications in Indigofera (Fabaceae) for South Australia. Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Gardens 24: 67 - 73, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23874288" title="New taxa and typifications in Indigofera (Fabaceae) for South Australia." url="https://www.jstor.org/stable/23874288" volume="24" year="2010">Wilson and Rowe 2010</bibRefCitation>
), its diagnostic features do not overlap with 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. monieriana" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="monieriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. monieriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new taxon is also remarkable for its articulate leaf rachis and its dark ferruginous colleters (multicellular thick secretory hairs) at the insertion of petiolules on the rachis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
